----------------------------FULL RESEARCH PLAN------------------------------------

1) Construct test object
    Construct a 15-stock portfolio (fixed universe; daily frequency).
    Collect historical daily prices for stocks and a benchmark (e.g., sector ETF + broad index) for risk adjustment.
2) Shock event dataset (primary data)
    Build a database of news events linked to the 15 stocks (headline, timestamp, source, type).
    Use ChatGPT-assisted NLP to extract:
        sentiment (positive/neutral/negative)
        event type (earnings, regulation, political, management, legal, etc.)
        optional: “urgency” or “fundamental vs transient” label
        Combine these into a Shock Score.
3) Manager assessment dataset (primary data)
    Use Microsoft Forms to collect manager assessments for the same news items:
        perceived severity (Likert 1–7)
        expected direction (up/down/uncertain)
        expected horizon (hours/days/weeks)
        recommended action (hold/reduce/add/hedge)
        confidence
    Target audience: portfolio managers / investment team members (aim ≥ 50 responses, as Stefano suggested).
4) “Do decisions show up in real portfolios?”
    Choose a mutual fund or strategy proxy (or a set of funds) and test whether public portfolio composition changes (holdings/weights when available) align with:
    manager assessments (your Forms data)
    the Shock Score
    Where holdings frequency is quarterly, treat this as medium-term validation, not “same-day reaction.”
5) Portfolio simulations (three strategies)
    Simulate and compare three portfolios:
        Manager-only decisions -- rebalancing driven by the survey decisions (aggregated rule).
        Manager + Shock Score support --  decisions informed by managers but adjusted/filtered by the score (decision-support layer).
        Shock Score only -- rule-based score strategy (baseline automation).
    Evaluate performance and risk, and test whether the score improves outcomes and/or decision consistency.
6) Conclusion
Test whether the Shock Score:
    improves risk-adjusted performance and drawdown behavior, and/or
    reduces decision noise and increases consistency relative to manager-only responses.

-----------------------------PROBLERMS------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Nuances to handle (so the design is defensible):

Mutual fund portfolio dynamics data is slow
Holdings are often quarterly/monthly, so use it as a separate validation track (“does anything persistent show up?”) 
rather than as proof of immediate reaction. For short-term reaction, rely on price/volatility event windows.

Define the unit of analysis clearly
Use event-level observations: each news item is one observation with:
    score features,
    manager response metrics,
    realized outcome metrics (abnormal return, volatility jump, drawdown impact).

Make “decision quality” measurable without philosophy
Operationalize it as:
    abnormal volatility capture after decision,
    reduction in adverse moves (drawdown / tail risk),
    improved risk-adjusted metrics,
    and optionally, “alignment” between manager expectation and realized direction.

“Behavioral correction tools” should be framed simply
Rather than deep behavioral modelling, use practical corrections like:
    thresholding (do not act unless severity exceeds X),
    confirmation delay (cool-off period),
    asymmetric response rules (loss aversion proxy),
    attention filter (ignore low-credibility/high-noise sources).


